  "prompt": "If I connect USB OTG pendrive to my power bank and connect the other point with data cable to my mobile, will pendrive be working on my mobile?",
  "response": "No, this setup won't work. Here's why:\n\n* **Power Banks Primarily Output Power:** Power banks are designed to *provide* power, not transmit data. They don't have the necessary circuitry to act as a data host or pass data through.\n\n* **USB OTG Needs a Host:**  USB OTG (On-The-Go) allows a device like your phone to act as a USB host, meaning it can recognize and control USB peripherals like flash drives.  Your phone has that capability.  However, the power bank is not designed to be a data host.\n\n* **Data Cables Transfer Data AND Power (Sometimes):** While a data cable *can* carry power, it also has the wires needed to transfer data.  However, it requires a device on each end that understands how to send and receive that data.\n\n**In short, you're creating a closed circuit where power is flowing, but no data is being communicated. Think of it like trying to listen to a radio through an extension cord \u2013 it just won't work.**\n\n**To use the pendrive on your phone, you need to:**\n\n1. **Connect the USB OTG pendrive DIRECTLY to your phone using a USB OTG adapter (if needed).**  Most modern Android phones with USB-C already support OTG; older ones might need an adapter.\n\n**Why this works:**\n\n* Your phone acts as the USB host.\n* The OTG adapter (if needed) allows the connection of the pendrive to your phone's port.\n* Your phone provides the necessary power and data communication to access the files on the pendrive.\n",
